      <section eId="sec_CCRP-770">
        <num>CCRP 770</num>
        <heading>770.  Prejudicial remarks; basis of mistrial</heading>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-770__subsec_1">
          <num>(1)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Race, religion, color or national origin, if the remark or comment is not material and relevant and might create prejudice against the defendant in the mind of the jury;</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-770__subsec_2">
          <num>(2)</num>
          <content>
            <p>Another crime committed or alleged to have been committed by the defendant as to which evidence is not admissible;</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-770__subsec_3">
          <num>(3)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The failure of the defendant to testify in his own defense; or</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-770__subsec_4">
          <num>(4)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The refusal of the judge to direct a verdict.
An admonition to the jury to disregard the remark or comment shall not be sufficient to prevent a mistrial.  If the defendant, however, requests that only an admonition be given, the court shall admonish the jury to disregard the remark or comment but shall not declare a mistrial.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <authorialNote marker="source">
          <p>Source: https://www.legis.la.gov/legis/Law.aspx?d=112767</p>
        </authorialNote>
      </section>
